text.tspan: NB by def of eval F = F.
We can identify objects (functors) of funct
cat [A,B] with functors 1->[A,B] and arrows
of A with functors 2->A.
Evaluating a functor F:A->B on an arrow h
of A gives an arrow of B which we can
identify with the composite of F and the
functor h:2->A representing h.
So (internal) functor evaluation can be done
by (external) functor composition; in turn,
this is the same as composing with the eval
arrow. (Exponential UMP)
Take an arrow of [A,B] and one of A and so (UMP) an
arrow of [A,B]xA; what arrow of B does evaluation yield?
We can work it out just by looking at external maps.
Note that every time we take an arrow of [A,B]
and one of A, we also have a commutative square
in [A,B]xA which evaluated yiedls a commutative
squre in B.
Again, we can compute its corners and edges
without looking at the inner arrows. (Just use
the above results and composition.)
